Weather Forecast Prediction¶

By Adegun Ahmed Olamilekan¶

Investigation Overview¶

Objective: The primary goal is to build a classification model that accurately predicts whether it will rain based on the input weather conditions.

Methodology: Dataset: The dataset file contains 6 columns with 2500 rows

Data Processing: Clean and transform the data for machine learning models

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA): Use suitable charts to uncover trends, correlations in the data.

Model Development: Use classification models like logistic regression, decision tree, and random forest to build the model

Model Evaluation: Use classification evaluation metrics to evaluate the model performance

Report: Comment on theoverallinsight

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 15))

# Subplot 1: Distribution of Temperature
plt.subplot(3, 2, 1)
sns.scatterplot(x=df.index, y=df['Temperature'], hue=df['Rain'])
plt.title('Scatter Plot of Temperature')
plt.xlabel('Index')
plt.ylabel('Temperature')


# Subplot 2: Scatterplot of Humidity vs. Rain
plt.subplot(3, 2, 2)
sns.scatterplot(x=df.index, y=df['Humidity'], hue=df['Rain'])
plt.title('Scatter Plot of Humidity')
plt.xlabel('Index')
plt.ylabel('Humidity')


# Subplot 3: Scatterplot of Wind_Speed vs. Rain
plt.subplot(3, 2, 3)
sns.scatterplot(x=df.index, y=df['Wind_Speed'], hue=df['Rain'])
plt.title('Scatter Plot of Wind_Speed')
plt.xlabel('Index')
plt.ylabel('Wind_Speed')


# Subplot 4: Scatterplot of Cloud_Cover vs. Rain
plt.subplot(3, 2, 4)
sns.scatterplot(x=df.index, y=df['Cloud_Cover'], hue=df['Rain'])
plt.title('Scatter Plot of Cloud_Cover')
plt.xlabel('Index')
plt.ylabel('Cloud_Cover')

# Subplot 4: Scatterplot of Pressure vs. Rain
plt.subplot(3, 2, 5)
sns.scatterplot(x=df.index, y=df['Pressure'], hue=df['Rain'])
plt.title('Scatter Plot of Pressure')
plt.xlabel('Index')
plt.ylabel('Pressure')


# Adjust layout
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The above graphs depict the relationships that exist between two attributs with regards to effect on the outcome on "rain" or "no rain".

It appears that there is more probability of an occurence of rainfall, where temperature seems to be lower, higher humidity and higher cloud cover.

## MODEL BUILDING
In [13]:
# develop Train dataset and target variable

X = df.drop(columns= "Rain")
y = df.Rain
In [14]:
# separate trainig set from test dataset

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X,y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)
In [15]:
# Build Random Forest Classifier Mode

rf_model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=500, max_depth=50)

rf_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

Summary of Findings¶

Accuracy¶

The overall accuracy of approximately 99.987%

Precision¶

Class 0 (No Rain): 1.00
Every time the model predicts "No Rain," it is correct. This is crucial for trust in dry weather predictions.

Class 1 (Rain): 1.00
Every prediction of "Rain" is accurate, avoiding unnecessary alarms

Recall¶

Class 0 (No Rain): 1.00
All true "No Rain" days are identified.

Class 1 (Rain): 0.99
99% of rainy days are correctly identified, with minimal misses. Missing even a small number of rainy days could matter depending on the use case, so continuous monitoring is advisable.

F1 Score¶

Class 0 (1.00): Perfect balance between precision and recall.
Class 1 (0.99): High reliability for predicting rainy days despite the small minority class.
